    "long_instructions": "# Do This:\r\n1. 🖥️ Run your code and observe the outcome.\r\n#\r\n2. 🖥️ Add a comment on line 5 to explain what the `while` loop does.\r\n#\r\n3. 🖥️ Uncomment the second section, lines 10-15. Run the code and observe how it performs the same task.\r\n#\r\n4. <i class=\"fa-solid fa-comment\"></i> **Discuss**: How does using the `move_and_paint()` function simplify your code?\r\n#\r\n5. 🖥️ **Modify**: Add a `painter.turn_right()` method after the `move_and_paint()` function call. Then call the `move_and_paint()` function a second time.\r\n    - *Hint: When making the painter turn, either create a new `turn_right` function or call the existing `painter.turn_left()` method 3 times.*\r\n    - <i class=\"fa-solid fa-comment\"></i> **Discuss**: *What happens when you reuse the `move_and_paint` function after making the Painter turn?*\r\n",
    "start_sources": {
      "files": {
        "0": {
          "id": "0",
          "name": "main.py",
          "language": "py",
          "contents": "from neighborhood import Painter\n\nfatima = Painter()\n\n# Add your comment here\nwhile fatima.can_move(\"South\"):\n   fatima.paint(\"yellow\")\n   fatima.move()\n   \n# def move_and_paint():\n#    while fatima.can_move(\"South\"):\n#      fatima.paint(\"yellow\")\n#      fatima.move()   \n\n# move_and_paint()",
